/800/cpsprodpb/72FB/production/_112953492__90021446_test_grey_line_new-nc.png 800w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/72FB/production/_112953492__90021446_test_grey_line_new-nc.png 976w" width="624" height="23" class="ssrcss-11yxrdo-Image edrdn950"/></picture></noscript></span></span></div></figure></div><div data-component="subheadline-block" class="ssrcss-19w8cxh-ComponentWrapper-HeadlineComponentWrapper egtrm1f0"><h2 id="4-Political-party-conferences-in-a-Covid-world" tabindex="-1" class="ssrcss-1ipj56t-Heading e10rt3ze0"><span role="text">4. Political party conferences in a Covid world</span></h2></div><div data-component="text-block" class="ssrcss-uf6wea-RichTextComponentWrapper ep2nwvo0"><div class="ssrcss-7uxr49-RichTextContainer e5tfeyi1"><p class="ssrcss-1q0x1qg-Paragraph e1jhz7w10">Coronavirus has robbed politicos of the chance to mingle in their hundreds at party conferences this autumn. Instead, Conservatives, Labourites and Liberal Democrats will have to watch their leaders speak via Zoom. The parties insist the events will be as vibrant and interesting as possible, but, as Labour&#x27;s gets under way this weekend, <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-54150015" class="ssrcss-f6h2dj-InlineLink e1kn3p7n0">what are the big things to look out for and how much has changed?</a></p></div></div><div data-component="image-block" class="ssrcss-xza2yt-ComponentWrapper ep2nwvo1"><figure class="ssrcss-8589xk-StyledFigure e34k3c23"><div class="ssrcss-ab5fd8-StyledFigureContainer e34k3c21"><span class="ssrcss-5zsoxt-Placeholder etlorgc0"><span><noscript><picture><source srcSet="https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/240/cpsprodpb/929B/production/_114413573_leaders.png.webp 240w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/320/cpsprodpb/929B/production/_114413573_leaders.png.webp 320w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/480/cpsprodpb/929B/production/_114413573_leaders.png.webp 480w, https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/929B/production/_114413573_leaders.png.webp 624w,